  "description": {
    "en": "Master named groups, lookahead/lookbehind assertions, re.sub for substitution, and compiled patterns for performance.",
    "ta": "named groups, lookahead/lookbehind assertions, re.sub மாற்றீடு, compiled patterns ஆகியவற்றில் தேர்ச்சி பெறுங்கள்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 70,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Advanced Decoder\n\nVaathiyaar upgrades the magnifying glass to a high-tech scanner. \"Basic regex finds patterns. Advanced regex **transforms** text, **extracts** structured data, and handles edge cases with lookahead and lookbehind.\"\n\n### Advanced Features\n\n| Feature | Syntax | Purpose |\n|---------|--------|----------|\n| Named Group | `(?P<name>...)` | Label captured groups |\n| Lookahead | `(?=...)` | Match only if followed by |\n| Lookbehind | `(?<=...)` | Match only if preceded by |\n| Non-capturing | `(?:...)` | Group without capturing |\n| `re.sub` | `re.sub(pattern, repl, text)` | Find and replace |\n| `re.compile` | `re.compile(pattern)` | Pre-compile for speed |\n\n### Named Groups\n\n```python\npattern = r'(?P<year>\\d{4})-(?P<month>\\d{2})-(?P<day>\\d{2})'\nmatch = re.search(pattern, '2025-03-27')\nprint(match.group('year'))  # 2025\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** Named groups make your regex self-documenting. Instead of `match.group(1)`, use `match.group('year')` — much clearer for maintenance."
  },
